## 1. Purpose & strategy (the why behind every decision)

This site is a **work-sample for the Amazon Brand Innovation Lab (BIL) India — Design
Technologist role.** BIL ships scroll-driven, animated, pixel-faithful branded landing pages.
So the site isn't a portfolio that *describes* the skill — it's built to *be* the skill on
display. Audience: a BIL hiring manager who opens the live URL on a phone and spends ~30
seconds before deciding.

- **The claim (what the site must land):** a rare developer who pairs resonant design with
  production-grade code to back it up.
- **The feeling (governs every visual/motion choice):** precise, calm, in control. When a
  choice feels flashy, it's probably wrong — reach for confident restraint.
- **Primary goal / one action:** the résumé download. Everything is arranged to build enough
  conviction that grabbing the résumé feels obvious. Contact is secondary.
- **Headline (locked, exact):** "Web experiences that resonate. Engineered to be fast,
  accessible, and measured."
- **Governing principle:** *demonstrate, don't assert.* Never write "I'm great at motion" —
  the page moves well and that is the proof. Every element must be showing, not telling.
- **The two differentiators (Tarun's real edges, both in the JD's preferred column):**
  accessibility (WCAG AAA background) and measurement (A/B + multivariate testing, analytics).
  Most motion-first applicants have neither. They must surface in the content, not be buried.
- **Honesty / scoping (hard rule):** no overclaims, no soft metrics he can't defend. Client
  work (AEM, Adobe, Palo Alto) is real experience he can *describe*, but the actual pages,
  code, brand assets, and screenshots are **not his to publish**. Anything shown must be his
  own clean-room work.

