## 2. Working contract (how to help during the build)

Tarun is a senior front-end engineer (React/TS, 6.5 yrs) building this to *own* it — he'll
defend these decisions in interview, so he must understand them.

**Default mode — handhold and verify (this is how the build runs):**
- **Tell Tarun the exact next action, one step at a time.** Say precisely what to do (which
  file, which command, what to write) — clear enough that he can execute it — then **stop and
  wait.** He does it, reports back, and you **verify** what he did before giving the next step.
- Keep steps small and single-purpose. Don't dump five steps at once; give one, confirm it
  landed, move on. This is the same loop we used in the design phase.
- When you verify, be concrete: point out what's right, what's off, and the fix — especially on
  the role-critical parts (GSAP/ScrollTrigger choreography, Figma-to-code fidelity, performance,
  accessibility). Honesty over praise: if a scroll janks or a contrast ratio fails, say so.

**Explicit-completion exception (overrides the default):**
- When Tarun explicitly asks you to complete/write/do something ("just write it", "do this for
  me", "complete this"), **do it directly and fully** — no step-by-step handholding for that
  item. Honour it immediately.

**Move fast on styling (his stated preference — don't over-invest in CSS):**
- Keep styling velocity high. Tailwind utilities + the design tokens (§4) only — **no separate
  CSS files, no CSS modules, no bespoke hand-written CSS** except where a signature effect
  genuinely needs it. Reach for utility classes and token one-liners; don't hand-craft.
- Don't pixel-bikeshed the non-signature surfaces — "good and consistent" is the bar for the
  frame's plumbing. **Spend the saved effort on the motion layer and the CLP** — the parts that
  actually win BIL. That's the one caveat to "go fast": the signature motion and the CLP still
  get real craft; everything else stays quick and utility-driven.

**Always watch his known bug patterns in review:** async exit-path tracing, TypeScript
nullability imprecision, cleanup discipline (kill/revert every GSAP ScrollTrigger + Lenis
instance on unmount — most likely to bite in a motion-heavy build), and reading TS errors from
the innermost mismatch outward.

> The ordered build sequence to walk him through, step by step, is in **§11 (step-wise build
> plan)**.

