## 6. Section-by-section spec (the portfolio frame)

Order top to bottom: **sticky nav → hero → selected work → differentiators band → footer.**
All sections share the container from §4.

### 6.1 Sticky nav
- **Structure:** wordmark left ("Tarun." — teal full-stop is an acceptable single accent use);
  right side: quiet text links (`Work`, `About`, `Contact`) that anchor-scroll to sections,
  plus the résumé CTA.
- **Styling:** links are quiet neutral text; the **résumé button is the one filled element**
  (teal fill, off-white label, download icon) — visually dominant, the eye always finds it.
- **Functionality:** sticky/fixed to top; condenses subtly on scroll (e.g. reduced height /
  faint bottom border / slight background blur once past the hero). Smooth-scroll on anchor
  links, offset for the sticky bar.
- **Responsive:** on mobile, collapse the three text links into a menu (or drop to just the
  résumé button + a minimal menu); résumé stays visible at all widths.
- **A11y:** `<nav aria-label>`, real anchor links, visible focus-visible states, keyboard order
  logical.

### 6.2 Hero
- **Structure:** contained column with side padding. Weighty, **left-aligned** headline
  (dominant element on the page). The one human **about line** sits *below* it as a supporting
  subline. **No hero CTA** (résumé already persistent in nav).
- **Background motion:** subtle, contained **to the hero only**, sitting **behind a
  semi-opaque overlay** so the foreground text always wins on contrast. Ambient, low-contrast,
  slow — atmosphere, not a competing animation.
- **Fold strategy:** deliberately let the top of Selected Work **peek above the fold** to bait
  the scroll.
- **Styling:** headline in Bricolage, large, high weight; subline in Inter, secondary colour.
- **Motion:** gentle entrance (fade + short rise on load, house easing). Respect reduced motion.
- **Responsive:** headline scales down (`clamp()`); stays left-aligned; overlay/motion perf-safe
  on mobile.

### 6.3 Selected work (the heaviest section — this is the proof)
- **Section heading:** short text heading "Selected work".
- **Project order (locked):** (1) **spec CLP — featured**, (2) micro-frontend multi-form
  project, (3) CMS-migration React work, (4) Partner Portal. Learning projects (social feed,
  guest-entry) are **cut** — no weak projects.

**Featured CLP card (the headline act — must read as unequal to the rest):**
- **Structure:** full-width card. Desktop: **text left** (heading + description), **motion
  preview right**. Mobile: **preview on top, heading + description below.**
- **Preview:** a lightweight, muted, **lazy-loaded** motion loop (shows the scroll craft — not
  a frozen frame). Keep it perf-safe (small file, `loading="lazy"`, poster).
- **Functionality:** the **whole card is a real link** to the CLP route — clickable by mouse,
  tap, and keyboard (Tab + Enter). The hover overlay (dims preview, reveals a "view the live
  experience" affordance) is a **pointer-only enhancement, never the sole path in.**
- **Styling:** larger, more prominent than the three below; a small "Featured · concept" tag.

**Three supporting cards:**
- **Structure:** heading + one-line description + a **high-level tag row** (3–4 tags max,
  e.g. `React · TypeScript · Micro-frontend`). Desktop: three in a row. Mobile: stacked column.
- **Functionality — important:** these are client-facing work, so they **do not link
  anywhere.** Therefore they **must not look clickable** — no hover-lift, no pointer cursor, no
  "read more". They are calm, static, informational tiles. The visible contrast (alive
  clickable CLP vs. quiet static three) reinforces the CLP as the headline.
- **Copy note:** since there's no link, the **description carries all the credibility** — each
  must state concrete, specific scope/outcome, never "worked on various features." (Copy TBD at
  content stage, grounded in real, defensible history.)

### 6.4 Differentiators band (accessibility + measurement)
- **Structure:** **no section header.** Two side-by-side columns: left = accessibility, right =
  measurement. Each = a strong heading + **one tight sentence.**
- **Styling:** **calm**, not flashy — the form must match the message (discipline). Prominence
  comes from **generous whitespace + type scale**, not a label. Lots of breathing room above and
  below so it stands alone as its own moment.
- **Responsive:** two columns stack on mobile.
- **Why it's placed here:** it lands *after* the proof, so the two claims read as the
  through-line of everything above rather than empty assertions — the last conviction-builder
  before the ask.

### 6.5 Footer (final conversion point)
- **Structure:** three links (LinkedIn, GitHub, `mailto:` email) on the left; **résumé button
  repeated** on the right; the **reduced-motion toggle** below-right. **No closing line** — go
  straight to links. **No contact form.**
- **Styling:** résumé button is again the one filled/dominant element (max-conviction moment);
  the three links are quiet. Reduced-motion toggle small and honest, with a state label
  (e.g. "reduced motion · off/on").
- **GitHub caveat (build task):** GitHub must not be a ghost town before linking — this repo
  (and the CLP) should live there, clean and public, so a curious engineer sees real code.
- **A11y:** toggle is a real `button` with `aria-pressed`; links have discernible names.

