## 7. The CLP page — centrepiece exhibit (fictional brand: TIMBRE)

**Status: fully specced.** Build the frame (§6) first — it establishes the tokens, motion
system, and engineering standards — then build the CLP inheriting that *engineering* DNA while
wearing its own *brand skin*.

### 7.1 Concept & honesty
- **Standalone route** (`/work/clp`), linked from the featured card; a full scroll-driven
  experience the visitor moves through, then returns to the portfolio.
- **Clean-room, fictional brand — TIMBRE**, a premium wireless audio brand (flagship product:
  *Studio One* over-ear headphones). No real brand IP, logos, or copied code.
- **Tagged clearly as a concept/spec build**, and its CTA is non-transacting (it's a
  demonstration, not a store).
- Rooted honestly in Tarun's **real AEM custom interactive-component work** (authored
  hero/carousel components with custom authoring). The *skill* is real and shipped; *this page*
  is a fresh demonstration. Keep that distinction clean in copy. (Thematic bonus, not required:
  an audio brand about *resonance* quietly echoes the portfolio headline "experiences that
  resonate.")

### 7.2 Why its own identity (design rationale — be able to defend it)
A branded landing page must look like the **brand**, not the designer. So the CLP gets its own
palette, type, and a deliberately more **immersive, cinematic** register that *contrasts* the
portfolio's light, calm, editorial frame. Demonstrating you can shift into a separate brand's
visual language at a high bar is literally the BIL job. The CLP **inherits the frame's
engineering DNA** (GSAP, easing discipline, a11y, performance) — **not** its skin.

### 7.3 Brand visual system (TIMBRE — distinct from the frame)
Colour — dark, immersive, premium, with a warm metallic accent (brand-appropriate; this is a
deliberate branded choice, not the "near-black + acid accent" default — the accent is warm
champagne, and the register is justified by the product category):
```
--tb-bg        #14161A   /* deep ink/graphite — immersive dark base */
--tb-surface   #1C1F24
--tb-text      #F2EFE9   /* warm off-white */
--tb-text-dim  #A7A399
--tb-accent    #C9A96A   /* warm champagne/brass — the brand accent */
--tb-accent-hi #E4C98A   /* lighter accent for small text if contrast needs it */
--tb-line      rgba(242,239,233,0.10)
```
Typography — its own voice (both free via `next/font/google`, deliberately different from the
frame's Bricolage + Inter):
- **Display: Syne** — distinctive, modern, design-forward; reads premium/confident. 600/700/800.
- **Body: Manrope** — clean geometric, a touch warmer than Inter. 400/500.

Spacing/rhythm — **more cinematic** than the frame: full-bleed sections, large type, generous
vertical space between story beats. Same 8px base for internal consistency.

Motion feel + easing — inherits the *discipline*, dials the *drama* up slightly for product
reveals. Own house curve `cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1)` (a stronger ease-out for cinematic
settles), stored as `--tb-ease`, used on every CLP tween. Same calm-but-considered family as
the frame; nothing bouncy.

### 7.4 Signature interaction (the CLP's memorable moment)
Carries the frame's idea — *motion with visible intent, always accessible* — expressed for the
brand:
1. **Scroll-scrubbed hero product** — the headphones subtly rotate/settle as you scroll the
   hero (scrubbed to scroll position, not autoplay).
2. **Variant carousel that re-themes the section** — selecting a colourway swaps the product
   *and* retints `--tb-accent` for the surrounding section, so the page responds to the choice.
   Distinctive, brand-appropriate, and it shows off state-driven theming.
Both **must** have reduced-motion fallbacks (static product; instant variant swap).

### 7.5 Section-by-section (structure · function · responsive · copy)
Copy below is starter text — refine in place; keep it plain and confident.

1. **Brand hero** — full-bleed dark, product as the focal element, quiet scroll cue.
   - Copy: headline "Hear the whole picture." · sub "Studio One — wireless over-ear headphones,
     tuned for people who listen closely."
   - Motion: scrubbed product settle + gentle text rise on load. Reduced-motion: static hero.
   - Responsive: product scales; headline `clamp()`; overlay behind text if legibility needs it.

2. **The promise (pinned + scrubbed)** — pinned section; short lines reveal on scrub.
   - Copy (in sequence): "Forty-hour battery." → "Adaptive noise cancellation." → "Studio-tuned
     40mm drivers."
   - Function: ScrollTrigger pin + scrub; each line fades/rises on its segment. Reduced-motion:
     unpinned, lines stacked and visible. Responsive: shorten pin distance on mobile.

3. **Parallax product moment** — full-bleed layered parallax, one evocative line.
   - Copy: "Engineered in silence, so every detail survives the noise."
   - Function: background / product / text at different speeds. Reduced-motion: flat, no parallax.

4. **Features (sticky)** — sticky copy column beside scrolling visuals, three features.
   - Copy: (a) "Silence on demand — hybrid ANC that adapts to the room." (b) "All day, and then
     some — 40 hours, 10-minute quick charge." (c) "Made to be worn — memory foam, 250g, balanced
     clamp."
   - Function: sticky text, visuals swap as each feature enters view. Reduced-motion: static
     stacked blocks. Responsive: stacks (visual over copy) on mobile.

5. **Interactive variant carousel (signature)** — colourway selector.
   - Variants: "Midnight" · "Champagne" · "Slate".
   - Function: selecting a variant swaps the product and retints the section accent
     (`--tb-accent`); keyboard-operable (focusable controls + arrow keys), swipe on touch.
     Reduced-motion: instant swap, no transition.

6. **Closing brand moment** — sign-off + spec CTA + honesty tag + back link.
   - Copy: "Studio One. Built to disappear, so the music doesn't." · button "Discover" (concept,
     non-transacting) · small tag "Concept / spec build — fictional brand, by Tarun." ·
     "← Back to portfolio" link.

### 7.6 A11y & performance (inherited, non-negotiable)
- Every effect has a `prefers-reduced-motion` fallback; the footer reduced-motion toggle governs
  the CLP too if the control is shared across routes.
- Semantic landmarks, keyboard-operable carousel, focus-visible, AA contrast (warm off-white on
  ink; verify champagne accent for any *text* use — fall back to `--tb-accent-hi` on small text).
- Lighthouse 100s: lazy-load heavy visuals, `next/image`, code-split the CLP route, kill/revert
  every ScrollTrigger + Lenis instance on unmount.

